evidence:
Single-node cassandra:5.0.4 pod in ns repro-20171 (pinned to kind-worker3), authz enabled via container command override (authenticator: PasswordAuthenticator, authorizer: CassandraAuthorizer, role_manager: CassandraRoleManager). Authz-live guard passed: LIST ROLES shows cassandra | True (superuser login works). In one cqlsh session (verbatim, Warning/Recommendation lines filtered):
  CREATE ROLE test ...;
  GRANT SELECT PERMISSION ON KEYSPACE system TO test;          -> success
  GRANT SELECT PERMISSION ON KEYSPACE system_schema TO test;   -> success
  GRANT SELECT PERMISSION ON KEYSPACE system_views TO test;
    <stdin>:1:InvalidRequest: Error from server: code=2200 [Invalid query] message="Resource <keyspace system_views> doesn't exist"
  GRANT SELECT PERMISSION ON KEYSPACE system_virtual_schema TO test;
    <stdin>:1:InvalidRequest: Error from server: code=2200 [Invalid query] message="Resource <keyspace system_virtual_schema> doesn't exist"
  LIST ALL PERMISSIONS OF test; -> only 2 rows (<keyspace system>, <keyspace system_schema>) with SELECT.
This is byte-identical to the Jira body. The within-version contrast (real keyspaces grantable, virtual keyspaces not, same image/session) rules out the auth-misconfig confounder and isolates the bug to virtual-keyspace resource resolution in GRANT.
